Be it resolved that the lack of attention from utility companies regarding double poles in our community be discussed.

136
00:09:08,549 --> 00:09:09,569
Vice President Mox.

137
00:09:10,970 --> 00:09:11,970
Thank you, Mr. President.

138
00:09:13,132 --> 00:09:25,919
First, I'd like to, I received a letter from Superintendent of WIRES, Steven Randazzo, and this is a recent happening, Mr. President.

139
00:09:25,980 --> 00:09:30,882
The letter is dated June 5th, 2017, and it's from Verizon.

140
00:09:31,583 --> 00:09:42,129
As we all know, National Grid, for many years in this community, was the custodian of all the telephone poles, or I should say, a good majority of the telephone poles in the city.

141
00:09:42,757 --> 00:09:52,942
And just recently, Verizon and National Grid reached an agreement on who the custodian of the poles are, and I think this is pertinent information for this council.

142
00:09:53,343 --> 00:09:59,806
So I'd like to read just a portion, Mr. President, as I stated dated June 5th, 2017 from Verizon.

143
00:10:00,447 --> 00:10:12,473
This is dear municipal official, this is to inform you that effective May 31st, 2017, National Grid and Verizon have reached an agreement that changes the way the two companies perform

144
00:10:12,923 --> 00:10:15,184
utility pole work in your community.

145
00:10:15,765 --> 00:10:19,147
The agreement updates operating procedures in place for more than 30 years.

146
00:10:19,967 --> 00:10:33,355
Under the new agreement, custodial areas where one or more other pole owner had assumed responsibility for replacing and installing new utility poles on a municipal basis have been eliminated.

147
00:10:33,875 --> 00:10:41,220
Instead, National Grid will be responsible for all replacements, relocations, and new installations of jointly owned poles.

148
00:10:41,996 --> 00:10:51,400
Verizon will be responsible for removing all jointly owned poles once the replacement pole is installed and all facility transfers are completed.

149
00:10:51,980 --> 00:11:06,406
So right now, Mr. President, according to this letter, Verizon will now be responsible for the removal of all double poles, which is brand new to this community and I think one that people should be aware of.

150
00:11:08,847 --> 00:11:19,175
I offer this resolution tonight, Mr. President, to address the lack of attention with utility companies to the number of double poles we have in the community.

151
00:11:19,816 --> 00:11:28,303
According to our Superintendent Owais, we have a little over 8,400 telephone poles within the community.

152
00:11:29,192 --> 00:11:38,339
And according to the latest list I just received, there are roughly 245 double poles in the community.

153
00:11:38,959 --> 00:11:47,565
So if you look at it as a street situation, almost one out of every three streets in our community has a double pole on it.

154
00:11:48,490 --> 00:11:59,313
Right now, the current list is Verizon has 88 poles that they're responsible for removing wires, and that's why the pole is still up, the double pole.

155
00:11:59,913 --> 00:12:07,035
National Grid has 51 poles they're responsible for, and Comcast has 101 poles.

156
00:12:07,795 --> 00:12:11,916
The city of Method, Mr. President, and I'm proud to report this,

157
00:12:12,757 --> 00:12:25,567
back several years ago, was on close to, I believe it was 90 to 100 poles, that we had fire call boxes that were still hooked up, and they were holding the utility companies from removing the double pole.

158
00:12:26,367 --> 00:12:31,331
To date, Mr. President, we have one double pole on the city of Method.

159
00:12:32,512 --> 00:12:41,719
And that is a huge accomplishment, and the Superintendent of Wires, Steven Randazzo, should be commended on his work

160
00:12:42,377 --> 00:12:51,460
Mr. President, for putting together a priority list and getting our city utility, which is the fire call box, off the poles, Mr. President.

161
00:12:51,920 --> 00:12:57,963
But double poles, as we know, are a blight to our community and a public safety concern to area residents.

162
00:12:58,583 --> 00:13:04,625
Utility companies are unresponsive and have no incentive to remove double poles in a reasonable time frame.

163
00:13:05,484 --> 00:13:10,889
The current system for moving polls is dysfunctional and the state law ineffective.

164
00:13:11,609 --> 00:13:22,619
Municipalities need a new approach that hold utility companies accountable, requiring better coordination and improved communication to resolve this problem.

165
00:13:23,580 --> 00:13:31,785
As we all know, Chapter 164, Section 34B forbids companies from keeping double poles up for more than 90 days.

166
00:13:32,546 --> 00:13:37,169
However, there is no penalty to the utility company for not complying with the law.

167
00:13:38,270 --> 00:13:44,474
On July 28, 2005, the Mass Supreme Court Judicial Court upheld a lower court ruling

168
00:13:45,088 --> 00:13:52,553
overturning a Bedford Mass bylaw, imposing a $100 a day fine for each set of double utility poles.

169
00:13:53,153 --> 00:13:59,197
The court ruled that only the state legislature has the authority to impose a fine for keeping double poles.

170
00:14:00,218 --> 00:14:07,983
So based on that decision back in 2005, Mr. President, I offered a council resolution on October 3rd

171
00:14:09,711 --> 00:14:32,061
2006, requesting our state delegation amend chapter 164, section 34B, allowing city or town to the ability to enact local ordinances or bylaws prohibiting double polls beyond the 90 days, punishable by a fine not to exceed a maximum of $100 per occurrence per day.

172
00:14:33,882 --> 00:14:34,082
Rep.

173
00:14:34,523 --> 00:14:35,123
Scortino

174
00:14:35,912 --> 00:14:57,357
Then on October 6, 2006, based on the council resolution, offered a sponsor to build, Mr. President, with that exact terminology, which would allow, it was House Bill 1675, which would allow local cities and towns to actually find these utility companies.

175
00:14:58,258 --> 00:15:02,959
And it got bantered around in the State House, and

176
00:15:04,622 --> 00:15:14,968
What ultimately ended up happening, from what I understand, is that the utility companies were upset.

177
00:15:16,229 --> 00:15:17,730
Let's see where, let's see.

178
00:15:21,012 --> 00:15:26,295
The utility companies, Mr. President, were upset because they said it was unfair.

179
00:15:27,163 --> 00:15:29,304
to find the custodian of the pole.

180
00:15:29,885 --> 00:15:39,390
For instance, at the time, if National Grid owned the pole, they also had Comcast, Verizon on the pole, and they may be the ones holding up the process.

181
00:15:39,850 --> 00:15:45,793
So they said, how can you find us as the custodian where these other utilities are holding up the process?

182
00:15:46,638 --> 00:16:00,269
And in my opinion, Mr. President, the responsibility of the utility company that's the pole owner, they have license agreements with all these other attachees that are on the pole.

183
00:16:01,090 --> 00:16:06,474
And their license agreement states that they have the authority to transfer wires

184
00:16:06,998 --> 00:16:08,399
at the attachee's expense.

185
00:16:08,859 --> 00:16:20,627
So if National Grid thought Comcast was taking too long removing their wires, under their license agreement, they can go in at the attachee's expense and remove the wires, and we can get rid of the double pole.

186
00:16:21,047 --> 00:16:29,352
So you can see how the ambiguity that's out there really lends itself to a process that is not functioning, Mr. President.

187
00:16:29,655 --> 00:16:34,636
And this has been an issue, as you can see, it dates back to 2006 and far beyond that.

188
00:16:35,756 --> 00:16:56,500
So what I want to offer tonight, Mr. President, with the hopes of getting approval from this council, is that the state create, and this would be the Department of Telecommunications, they create, Mr. President, a statewide database

189
00:16:57,471 --> 00:17:00,793
which they oversee and they enforce.

190
00:17:01,293 --> 00:17:24,926
Right now, there's a database called Poll Lifetime Management System, and all the utility companies, it's PLM, all the utility companies and many municipalities have access to this system, so they can go online and look at these reports, which I have a copy in front of me, that states who's on the poll, how long the poll's been there, and who's responsible for taking their wires off.

191
00:17:25,947 --> 00:17:30,409
And they have access to this system, but there's no oversight by the state.

192
00:17:30,969 --> 00:17:47,094
So my request tonight through a motion of this council is that we request our state delegation to file legislation creating the statewide enforcement and penalty structure under the oversight and responsibility of the Mass.

193
00:17:47,114 --> 00:17:48,515
Department of Public Utilities.

194
00:17:49,435 --> 00:17:55,097
And by doing so, Mr. President, we'll create a state entity that's responsible for the oversight

195
00:17:55,814 --> 00:18:06,357
and also serve as an online tracking process that allows review of the state and possible finding by the state.

196
00:18:06,717 --> 00:18:08,638
So the municipalities don't have to get involved.

197
00:18:09,098 --> 00:18:10,798
It's the utility, Mass.

198
00:18:10,818 --> 00:18:16,460
Department of Public Utilities, which currently right now is the oversight for utilities in Massachusetts.

199
00:18:16,860 --> 00:18:20,201
They should step up to the plate and take responsibility.

200
00:18:20,695 --> 00:18:28,721
So that would be my recommendation tonight, Mr. President, that our state delegation file legislation to allow enforcement by Mass.

201
00:18:28,741 --> 00:18:33,385
